segments.text: Now, you were in the athletic department until what year?
Summer of 67.
So that's how many years?
Well, it's roughly around 10.
10. Who, as on the rest of the campus,
outside athletics, who were the people that you turned to?
The teachers.
Well, there must have been some key assistant deans or associate deans.
Well, sure.
I worked through the teacher first, and then the deans when it came to the
tallying up grade points and so, and there were always kids that were sliding.
One of my main pet guys was old Robert Cortez.
I didn't let him take English for four semesters and then he made B's the rest of the way.
And I told Dee Powell when they were, Bob was having a hard time
I guess as a guard and they moved him tackle and he was outstanding.
I said he just could not you know he got to have little chunks and stay with him because he was and he's down the valley coaching has been for years.
Uh all right in admissions uh who did you work with most closely?
Well the first year uh with with Coach Myers
I don't know whether you were ever familiar with the registrar's office.
You sent a transcript.
Finally, it was illegal, but I had the people from the public schools send them to me, and I would carry them over there.
There would be a little old girl who goes through, and she checks all of these, one chemistry, one biology, and so forth.
And then those that are deviant from that, they go to Mr. Cramer.
and go into Mr. Perriman's office and the damn things.
Now, this is not all athletes, but they were in there.
Stacked up.
And then if he could make a decision, the next level, they went to Mr. Heaton.
And, of course, we had the same problem through Ms. Mitchell if they were transferred from the junior college.
Let me interrupt.
I need to... All right, we were about to talk about Lloyd Heaton.
Oh, thank you.
Describe him and his functions and habits.
Well, Lloyd Heaton was the director.
I don't know what his exact title was.
We just called him the registrar in those days.
He was in charge of the registrar's office.
They had Miss Mitchell for transfer students.
Mr. Pearman was his assistant.
Milton Edge.
And then Jim Alexander, I guess, did the graduate check.
He was on the scholarship committee, the admission committee, academic county, and the executive committee.
And here we start battling it.
Yes, oh gosh, I just, I know one time, you remember when, were you here when
He was kidnapped.
The guy was in his car and made him go by the bank and withdraw some money.
And they took off.
About 9 o'clock that night, the phone rang.
They said, Elmer.
I said, is something wrong, Elmer?
And he said, no.
He said, I just want to know why you did it.
Why did I do what?
He said, kidnap me.
But we had running gun battles.
Shelby and I did on basketball players.
And I went to the conference two different times.
And they were wrong.
To get people admitted?
Their criteria was wrong.
Now, was Mr. Heaton, was he...
He's a head stick.
Was he comparatively...
Arbitrary.
Arbitrary.
That's a personal opinion.
That's right.
All right.
Now, by your use... Well, on this bunch, back up to Mr. Heaton.
Coach Myers.
I said, well, Coach, these kids don't meet admission requirements.
She said, what should I do about it?
I said, you need to call Mr. Rutter.
And so I called the list, you know, because I'd interviewed most of the kids during the spring.
We go up there and we're sitting, there's Mr. Heath, Mr. Rutter,
Coach Myers and Bud Denton, and we're sitting around the General's desk there.
Those were experiences that are just wonderful for me.
And he said, what's the problem here, Bud?
I said, well, we have some students that are late getting their applications in, and some of them have this difficulty.
And he turned to Mr. Heaton and he said, well, we'll lose our accreditation.
I can still see.
And he turned to me and he said, well, what do you think, bud?
I said, well, I think the kids can do the work, Mr. Ernie.
He said, okay, I want their grades on my desk every grade period.
Mr. Heaton, here's the list.
Take care of it.
That was it.
I had my, and he gave me an exit interview when I left.
I just, I was flattered, really.
Now, Mr. Heaton predates you on the campus.
Oh, yeah.
That lady, Sarah Holmgreen, her husband's dad was, I guess, the financial man back, way back.
And Mr. Heaton then served under many different presidents.
Oh, yeah, indeed.
Well, I don't think he was ever under a dean.
And retired for reasons of age.
There was no scandal or anything else.
Oh, well, there was one case.
I've got to tell you, Bob Murray was the academic...
person.
I can't remember where he was, what dorms and then breezy was in law hall and had charge of my athletes later when we moved to law and 15 Murray called me one day.
He said, Can you come up here?
And I went up stairs.
He said,
You know the registrar hadn't moved into the new officers.
That was that little building there.
And he had a set of keys in his hand.
He said, you know what these are?
No.
He said, these are the keys to Mr. Heaton's office.
And they hadn't even moved in.
So he had called the boy.
Asked him for any extra keys.
I don't know where he got them until this day.
Some kid, probably one of his dorm supervisors, had gotten them.
Some kid had come up to him and found them or had them.
They still don't know where they came from.
Out of his desk?
What were Mr. Heaton's pet peeves?
His way.
Going my way.
That's terrible.
Knowing that,
How would you and your colleagues, how would you all work it?
Oh, I didn't work around him.
I just went to his office when it got down to that and always carried my little handbook from the conference, you know.
All right.
Now, when you, the two of you disagreed, did he carry a grudge later?
Oh, no.
I never had that feeling.
He was against the basic division for some reason because, one, I know back over the years, Dee and I had worked together.
I don't know whether you were here or not, but we had put footprints to register.
And I don't know what it was, but we had the scholastic officers and non-coms in each of the units.
And they would bring them over, and we'd worked out all this mechanics, you know, that military type stuff.
And I know, went out there, one registration, and Mr. Perrymore was just beside himself.
He said, where are the troops?
Well, we'd already finished registration.
He couldn't believe it.
In a couple of hours.
That was registration during all your years in Sabisa.
Then, don't I remember, some summer registrations in G. Raleigh?
No.
That's later?
I used to.
pull the athlete's card, you know, they do first.
And I'd always get Alice's and register for her all over again.
Right now, where did the students eat in registration time?
Over at Duncan.
Oh, that's right.
Everybody ate at Duncan briefly.
Or the MSC.
And am I correct in remembering that almost every faculty member
took a little turn at registration.
Oh, yeah.
I know the history did in English.
You know, it was possible, the secretaries, and of course there was no objection in the early days of your teacher assignment list where they had them.
Now, math would turn up, unfortunately, with a bunch of sections that
never had teachers assigned to them, but there were good math teachers, and if you could do those types of things.
Who were those good math teachers?
Well, I thought Jack Kent was for upper level.
John Kinkenny.
Kubrick Kent.
Yeah, he'd be upper level, and I was trying to think of guys in my
was in my church.
What about in English?
Oh, Sid Cox and Jernigan and Louis Hauer.
Oh, they were a bunch of good people.
Chemistry?
Well, Callaway, one of the years he was here.
Biology?
Oh, Medlin Dobson.
He had a bunch of graduate students that taught.
They were superb teachers.
I had a few of them as tutors later.
Before they became graduates.
History?
I was partial to history anyway.
I thought the whole department.
Economics was a little more difficult.
I had majored in English.
Economics 203 and 4 when I was a student.
I wish I had taken them.
I did take them both over when I came back.
Were you at the Aspirations Report in the early 60s?
Is that big self-study?
Oh yeah, I have a copy somewhere.
Alright.
Did you have any... No.
Okay.
Austin will have to tell you because we just did assign tasks on Rudder's deal for the military.
I've got a copy of that someplace.
I haven't unpacked my stuff from 13 years ago that's moving from high school.
What do you now think about the aspirations report and its importance?
Well, I'd feel better if I knew who was on it.
I don't know anybody, you know.
But you know some of the recommendations, non-compulsory core.
Oh, you mean that one back?
Yeah.
Oh, yeah.
The fact is I had made a study of my class, I guess five years out from what I assumed was the normal graduation of class of 45.
And it turned out that the girls in the family outnumbered the boys 3-2.
There were some later high-powered guys in there.
Of course, they're nuts.
Some of these Aggies, you know, they just get carried away.
I was listening to Hall, and I knew him back when he was a freshman.
These stories that if people evaluate A&M on those stories...
Anyway.
All right, let's see.
Then let's go back to athletics.
Myers, then Fulberg.
Which coach, all the coaches you worked with, the football coaches, Bryant, Myers, Fulberg, Stallings.
I was two years with Gene.
All right.
Describe, you mentioned Myers.
Well, Hank had been my roommate.
when we were here at A&E.
He went into service after I did and I guess Blake was head stick at West Point.
He picked up him and Yeoman and Youngfold there.
They were all here.
Yeah, make believe I didn't know this Fulberg.
Tell me his name and where he was from.
Henry Fulberg, Oak Cliff, Dallas.
Played at Sunset.
Sunset Bison.
I used to go with his sister.
So we were, you know.
But I was disappointed he didn't have a strong coaching staff.
Old Craig was probably the...
The best one.
He was a PhD in history.
Like Jones, you know, from Colgate.
I do.
I had forgotten that.
Oh yeah.
We still correspond.
The fact is, when we were recruiting, when Hank was here, we'd have these Pennsylvania kids and their parents, when they came out, they'd come out here and we'd have supper and everything.
And I, Liptack, does that rank?
Yeah, John Liptack.
I don't think he played much football, but he's a big wheel down in Houston.
Were, was Coach Fulberg different from the others in his academic concerns?
Oh no, he was strong academically.
In fact, he was the one, really when you get down to it, that made the big changes in athletics.
We centralized the housing, centralized the food,
you know, if you weren't in season, you were just kind of, and he didn't buy it.
And this one, going to class.
We had a bad situation over there, and of course Hoyle had already gone many years, but Hart Hall had always been a sinkhole, really.
And he went over there, pulled a surprise inspection, his head athletic director,
He was most displeased in lunch that day.
He told him that he would be back there at 1 o'clock.
That place better be spotless.
He went back at 1 o'clock, and it was fun.
Now, who lived in Henderson and who lived in Hart Hall?
Football, basically, and the top kids of basketball.
In Henderson?
In Henderson.
And all other sports?
Over and hard.
And then we got, later on, we got part of law.
And there were almost, oh, married athletes.
A few.
Well, that was the problem.
We had day students, a day student military unit, and then we had the Air Force and Army and HART and the Air Force and Army and Henderson and Law.
And we got all those moved to 15 right across from Henderson and Law for the overflow.
We changed the commandant.
Hank went to the commandant and he changed their drill period for football from Saturday, can you imagine?
Moved all the drills to two.
Air Force and Army, all four.
Then the following year, when Tom Murrah, or it may have been two years later, when Tom Murrah was sealed with the infantry outfit, they were the top.
You can't tell me athletes can't march.
I'm not going to buy that.
But they were both premium outfits.
And you look back on that sort of thing, and it doesn't appear anywhere.
Nobody will know anything about it, but it's there.
Gosh, with the women's program, that must be a real challenge.
All right, now, with the three head coaches that came after Coach Bryant, Myers, Fulberg, and then Stallings, they all...
did not remain because they didn't win enough games.
I wrote Jim Meyers' speech or his presentation that he was going to leave.
I said, you know, you low-key this and leave.
Well, he got up there and just went berserk in a sense.
But they had told him he was staying.
That was the bad part.
Told him he was staying?
Regardless of the Texas game.
Oh, oh, oh.
And then?
And then Axton.
Right.
He had a board, really.
All right, you're saying they.
As far as you know, it was the board.
Oh, absolutely.
Okay.
But it was not the president.
Well.
As far as you know.
As far as I know.
All right.
Then Stallings is hired.
But nobody knew it.
Bones didn't know.
Hank damn sure didn't know.
Describe Starling's arrival and reaction and so forth.
The only thing I know is that we were told to come down to the lounge and he was introduced here as Hank.
All right, now, all of you knew Starling's.
Well, I knew him from student days.
What was the general reaction?
Well, I guess the former students must have seen him as a reincarnation of Coach Bryant.
He was only 29, and he was smart enough to keep Elmer Smith here with him.
And Elmer was a, you know, he was that follow-a-type guy.
Elmer was a coach?
A line coach, defensive coach.
He was really good.
I remember sitting up when Coach Bryant was here,
sitting up on that old scoreboard.
They had a stand out there.
And Elmer was checking the defenses.
And he'd go in at halftime.
You'd see the chains that came over.
If it was bad.
It was never too bad.
Even in the worst days, they were excellent.
Did Coach Stallings change any of the routine for all of y'all?
All of those people were very gracious to me.
They just, you know, you go through the trauma of whether you're going to have a job when the new coach comes in.
But each one of those people told me right off, we need you type thing, which was, I appreciate it.
Of course, I was getting up into my hole.
40s, you know.
Let's see, and all right, now you then leave and what?
Go to public schools.
Why did you leave?
Well, they had been after me and they had a lady over there, Ms. Dow, who was a widow, and
She was ready to retire.
Of course, I had a good reputation in the community, so they asked me.
Did they pay you more money?
Absolutely.
I couldn't believe it.
And I got credit for my 18 years.
Oh, and this is what year?
Okay.
As you look back, what were the key...
steps, decisions?
Only made two.
No, no, not you, but the institution made during those years, whether you had a hand in them or not.
Well, I think first of all was the co-education.
Of course, we had old boys.
It wasn't a problem with me, but that little old brief study I made of about 100 classmates who returned their questionnaires.
And then of course we made that study for Mr.
Rudder about the military and the changes there.
And of course being married with no children at the time, it was ideal for Alice to finish.
They'd go during the summer and they had a few classes, I recall.
She says not after three o'clock for the women, veterans' wives.
But she got her degree.
She was an honors student.
In the aspirations report, I was the secretary and wrote the first part.
And one of the arguments we made was that if we didn't co-educate and make the core non-compulsory, we said we're afraid we'll be very small and very narrow.
That's right.
Kind of like VMI and the Citadel.
We may have been a junior college.
Yeah.
Then we said if we don't go through racial integration, we're going to end up in the courtroom.
We didn't know about Title IX coming ahead in the future.
Well, I think they've always been ahead.
Yeah.
That's one, you know, I don't, less does the athletics, and I just do my century and other contributions to the A&M Club, but I just, they do a good job.
It's too big.
That would be my main criticism.
I think we should have cut off maybe a little less.
If the enrollment had been capped, should we then have become much more selective?
Do we pick
If we admit 5,000 a year, do we admit the best 5,000 that apply?

I can't buy this selective admission because I've worked with too many students over the years that, in fact, Billy Lay was always very gracious to me, but he could tell me in a nice way, no, you know.
But I had several little old gals out there, straight A.
They went to summer school, you know, that was the thing.
You had to take 12 hours, a high-ranking graduate student.
And there were many of those.
How would you have decided?
I don't know.
The first hundred.
I don't really know.
You know, it's kind of like the Opportunity Awards.
You've got less spots than you've got people.
What about this man, Earl Rudder?
How important was he?
I thought he was, this stool would have been down the drain if it hadn't been for Mr.
Rudder and then subsequently Jack Wood.
Because that, you know, I've been, the military showed me that.
Boy, you've got to have that leadership.
And I remember talking to Mr.
Rudder on that exit interview, and he said, well, what can we do about this?
What can we do about this?
Asking my opinion.
I just couldn't give him much.
Can you give examples of where you think Mr.
Rudder demonstrated his leadership ability?
Well, he made some mistakes, but he went out and got all those National Science Foundation.
God, you talk about a rock.
But you have to work through that.
And you remember Zener said that everybody in math and science will take their test on Tuesday night.
Well, Alice, you know Haskell?
Good to see you.
Thank you.
Myers got that straightened out, too.
He brought it to Mr.
Rudder's teacher because I don't think he knew about it.
And the kids were going to play Wednesday games, you know, the freshman.
Missing their exam, couldn't take it.
Get a zero.
That won't wash.
But anyway, I thought he was, I knew him personally, and I had gone, in fact, his Margaret Rutter's brother and I were freshmen in the same outfit.
Did you work with young Ed Cooper any?
Just knew him when he was the,
I mean, the president's assistant.
I always liked Ed.
And what was his function as far as you knew?
We used to call them in the Army dog robbers.
Everything, like they did me, well, let Ed take care of it.
He can handle that.
And he could write, boy, and speak, you know.
Like, I never thought that Mr.
Rudder was a particularly good speaker.
Oh, no.
But I also thought he never claimed to be either.
No.
The first time I heard him, I was a class agent, so I was on the inner sanctum for about 30 years.
Went over to the mid-winter conference, and he'd just been hired.
Got up from there and said, it's my happy privilege, you know,
just that old, I could go back to the hills of East Tennessee, and he said, now I want to make a statement here so that there won't be any question about your understanding.
He said, these people who say that they were my freshman roommates were not.
I went to John Talton for two years before I came to A&M.
of course that kind of big government.
Do you remember any other good rudder stories to share?
No, I just never had other than the exit interview and one time there was a question about a boy's grades that he wanted me to check.
And you remember Carl Swatan?
I kept a book on Carl because he was trouble.
You knew it just as soon as I...
When you see some people, and that's not fair, I'm sure, but I said, boy, I better document this.
And I did.
And his dad raised all kinds of hell.
Couldn't get him out.
And he flunked Dan Davis's course.
And I had how many conferences I'd had with Dan.
How many absences?
This guy had 12 or 14 absences.
Never turned in any work.
And that was just that course.
And there were others.
And I had put all this down.
Typed it out for Mr.
Rudder.
And he told these board members, here's the case.
The guy is not eligible.
But he tried to get into Navarro.
And then he went to Clemson.
Then he signed Crowe and got picked up stealing the playbook from the New Orleans Saints.
I guess he's over at Huntville now, I don't know.
Let's see, what are some of your proudest moments as you look back on your A&M years?
Well, I really couldn't tell you.
I was turned in, Pete Hardesty beat me out for that best award the first year they gave it, do you remember?
Dealing with personnel.
There were only five or four awards that year, but he beat me out on that.
But just to be turned in by your teachers for me.
And then, of course, we're real proud of our class, the class of 45.
There was a lot of sacrifice, you will see, in Scruggs putting together a real nice book.
Let's see, if you could go back to the years as an employee and change anything, what would you change?
I couldn't because I don't have any insight at all for that.
Okay.
Just size-wise, maybe.
All right, as we're getting close to the end of this part, now we'll go back and talk about your student years after a little bit.
Well, I'm going to have to.
Can we?
Oh, okay.
Okay.

right give me go ahead give me about another 10 minutes oh yeah yeah all right do you have any personal papers or any other memorabilia that if you ever have any that you want to part with please give it to the archives at the cushing library yeah particularly if they're i've been kind of waiting on a lot of that stuff because we we did keep a lot of
The fact is there's a little deal we did in A Company Infantry when the war broke out.
We got together and signed this deal and we're going to meet in Dallas on such and such a period after the war is over.
For example, if nothing else, let them make a Xerox copy.
